	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>World Bank review of unfinished business in the WTO negotiations </h1>

			
			<h4>
												09 December 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The World Bank has published a book reviewing the unfinished business in the WTO Doha Round. The editors of the book, in an online summary of the contents, maintain that WTO trade negotiators face what they describe as a ‘trilemma’, namely whether ‘to implement all or part of the draft agreements as they stand today; to modify them substantially; or to dump Doha and start afresh’.</p><p>The editors argue in the summary that one obstacle to an agreement is ‘widespread skepticism about what the DDA will actually deliver in terms of market access’. However it is pointed out that ‘after allowing for flexibilities such as for sensitive and special products’, the existing proposals would ‘cut applied tariffs on agricultural and non-agricultural (NAMA) goods by around 20 percent’. They maintain that the existing proposals would generate global gains ‘conservatively estimated’ at US$160 billion per year, but likely to be even larger since the commitments made ‘would reduce the uncertainty associated with the current large gaps between applied and bound tariffs’. However they note that limiting the duty-free, quota-free market access offer for LDCs by even as little as 3% of tariff lines ‘would sharply reduce the value of this market access’.</p><p>In addition, the summary notes that the agriculture sector proposals include a commitment to ‘abolition of export subsidies and sharp reductions in maximum levels of domestic support, especially in the EU and the USA’. On the sensitive issue of special safeguards, the World Bank analysis maintains that the evidence reviewed suggests that ‘the proposed SSM envisaged for developing countries, with quantity and price triggers, could both reduce market access and increase the instability of world and domestic markets.’</p><p>In terms of a possible broader agenda in the agriculture sector, the book argues that the current ‘limited disciplines on export restrictions hurt the confidence of importers that world markets would be a reliable source of food supplies’. It is maintained that ensuring ‘disciplines on both import and export restrictions, and dealing explicitly with both food security and price insulation issues could lead to a more desirable negotiated outcome’.</p><p>The book needs to be seen against the backdrop of the recent G20 statement, which acknowledged that ‘it is clear that we will not complete the DDA if we continue to conduct negotiations as we have in the past’, and the consequent call for ‘fresh, credible approaches to furthering negotiations’.</p><p>Meanwhile, according to a recent article by ICTSD, ‘consensus on a host of topics’ remains elusive. In terms of non-DDA issues, and in addition to proposals from the C4 cotton producing countries, ‘net food importing developing countries have argued in favour of a work programme on food price volatility’. The G90, which includes the ACP group, are looking to table proposals ‘on mainstreaming development within the scope of the Committee on Trade and Development’. Proposals have also been made ‘to exempt humanitarian food purchases from agricultural export restrictions’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>World Bank, ‘Unfinished business? The WTO’s Doha Development Agenda’, edited by W. Martin and A. Mattoo, summary of findings, November 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://siteresources.worldbank.org/INTTRADERESEARCH/Resources/Martin_Mattoo_Unfinished_Business_Doha.pdf" target="_self">http://siteresources.worldbank.org/INTTRADERESEARCH/Resources/Martin_Mat...</a></p><p>World Bank and Centre for Economic Policy Research, ‘Unfinished business? The WTO’s Doha Development Agenda’, eds. W. Martin and A. Mattoo, web page summarizing contents and giving point of access to download full document, 8 November 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://voxeu.org/index.php?q=node/7238" target="_self">http://voxeu.org/index.php?q=node/7238</a></p><p>ICTSD, ‘Consensus remains elusive as WTO Ministerial looms’, <i>Bridges Weekly Trade News</i><i>Digest</i>, Volume 15, No. 38, 9 November 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://ictsd.org/i/news/bridgesweekly/117966/" target="_self">http://ictsd.org/i/news/bridgesweekly/117966/</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>It is unclear whether existing WTO disciplines on export refunds and domestic agricultural support will actually have any meaningful effect on the external effects of the deployment of agricultural trade policy tools. For example, the surge in EU SMP exports in 2010–11 (which includes a 68% increase in exports to West Africa) occurred as a result of the expansion of EU intervention buying in response to the dairy market crisis in the EU. It took place without the benefit of expanded export refund allocations, as volatile prices allowed the EU to clear stocks without any significant expansion of export refund payments.</p><p>While the precise effects of EU safety-net interventions on the functioning of milk supply chains in West Africa is to date unclear, it remains an area of concern. The challenge is what kind of international rules and standards of practice need to be developed to ensure that the legitimate use of policy instruments by OECD countries within WTO rules do not have unintended consequences that undermine the efforts of ACP governments to promote agricultural development in specific sectors (e.g. in the dairy sector).</p><p>Some of these concerns may need to be addressed outside the DDA framework, for example through the work programme on food price volatility.</p><p>It is unclear, finally, what impact any WTO rules exempting humanitarian food purchases from agricultural export restrictions, would have on intra-regional trade in cereals in ACP countries (e.g. within the EAC).</p>
		</div>
		
